Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Caption", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This Demonstration illustrates the relationship between a rectangular pulse \
signal and its Fourier transform. There are three parameters that define a \
rectangular pulse: its height ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["A", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ", width ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " in seconds, and center ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["t", "0"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". Mathematically, a rectangular pulse delayed by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["t", "0"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " seconds is defined as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"g", "(", 
     RowBox[{"t", "-", 
      SubscriptBox["t", "0"]}], ")"}], "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"A", " ", 
      RowBox[{"rect", "(", 
       FractionBox[
        RowBox[{"t", "-", 
         SubscriptBox["t", "0"]}], "T"], ")"}]}], "=", 
     FormBox[
      RowBox[{"\[Piecewise]", GridBox[{
         {"A", 
          RowBox[{
           TemplateBox[{FractionBox[
              RowBox[{"t", "-", 
                SubscriptBox["t", "0"]}], "T"]},
            "Abs"], "\[LessEqual]", 
           FractionBox["1", "2"]}]},
         {"0", 
          TagBox["otherwise",
           "PiecewiseDefault",
           AutoDelete->False,
           DeletionWarning->True]}
        },
        GridBoxAlignment->{
         "Columns" -> {{Left}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, 
          "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
        GridBoxItemSize->{
         "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, "Rows" -> {{1.}},
           "RowsIndexed" -> {}},
        GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
            Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
             Offset[0.84]}, 
            Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "ColumnsIndexed" -> {}, 
          "Rows" -> {
            Offset[0.2], {
             Offset[0.4]}, 
            Offset[0.2]}, "RowsIndexed" -> {}}]}],
      TraditionalForm]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " and its Fourier transform or spectrum is defined as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"G", "(", "f", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"A", " ", "T", " ", 
     RowBox[{"sinc", "(", 
      RowBox[{"\[Pi]", " ", "f", " ", "T"}], ")"}], 
     RowBox[{"exp", "(", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"-", "i"}], " ", "2", " ", "\[Pi]", " ", "f", " ", 
       SubscriptBox["t", "0"]}], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 "."
}], "Text"]
}, Close]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This Demonstration illustrates how changing ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"g", "(", "t", ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " affects its spectrum. Both the magnitude and phase of the spectrum are \
displayed."
}], "Text"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Details", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell["\<\
This Demonstration illustrates the following relationship between a \
rectangular pulse and its spectrum:\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "1. As the pulse becomes flatter (i.e., the width ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " of the pulse increases), the magnitude spectrum loops become thinner and \
taller. In other words, the zeros (the crossings of the magnitude spectrum \
with the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["x", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis) move closer to the origin. In the limit, as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " becomes very large, the magnitude spectrum approaches a Dirac delta \
function located at the origin."
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
2. As the height of the pulse become larger and its width becomes smaller, it \
approaches a Dirac delta function and the magnitude spectrum flattens out and \
becomes a constant of magnitude 1 in the limit. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "3. As ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["t", "0"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " changes, the pulse shifts in time, the magnitude spectrum does not change, \
but the phase spectrum does. "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "4. We notice a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"180", "\[Degree]"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " phase shift at each frequency defined by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   FractionBox["k", "T"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"k", Cell["", "InlineMath"]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 "is an integer other than zero, and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " is the pulse duration. These frequencies are the zeros of the magnitude \
spectrum."
}], "Text"]
}, Close]],

